What happens if

```python
string_parameters = {
    'foo': ':bar',
    'bar': 'bummer'}
```

Instead of doing this JQuery work here in the ``initiate`` function, you would do better to just set some scope variables outside this function in the main area like this:

    $scope.parsedLog = parsedLog;
    $scope.fullLog = fullLog;
    if ($scope.isReftest()) {
        $scope.reftest = reftest;
    }

Then in the HTML, for your ``<a`` elements, you just do  ``href="{{ fullLog }}"`` and it picks up the value from the scope.

here this is not links as you suggested with `:class:` because `./run-tests.sh` returns me errors as it can't find the classes.
see http://stackoverflow.com/questions/11417221/sphinx-autodoc-gives-warning-pyclass-reference-target-not-found-type-warning
if you succeed to make it work, please tell me how :)

@lnielsen do you mean something like:
```python
return DynamicPermission(ParameterizedActionNeed('admin-access', admin_view.name))
```
?

...oh, weird. The trait does not really make sense then, afaict? Rather than:
```
impl<'a> ToMdbValue for &'a [u8] {
    fn to_mdb_value<'b>(&'b self) -> MdbValue<'b> {
```
it would need to be:
```
impl<'a> ToMdbValue for &'a [u8] {
    fn to_mdb_value(self) -> MdbValue<'a> {
```

As it stands, it requires a "reference to a reference", and there is nothing keeping the inner reference alive.

That's not how it works:

```
if True:
    if False:
        print "one"
else:
    print "two"
```

This won't print anything, because the `else` clause is attached to the first `if`, not the second one.  If have an if-elif-else chain, if it goes into any of the branches of the chain, it exits the entire block.
